# Decision -- Load and sanity-check the raw FY2025 daily sales data

Runtime: Sales MIS Guru Runtime
Cycle: 1
Model: anthropic/claude-opus-4-8
Status: decided

## Intent

> Load and sanity-check the raw FY2025 daily sales data
>
> Do steps 1 and 2 of the Sales MIS Workflow this cycle only: load the raw workbook and run the sanity check it describes. Stop once the clean staged dataset and the anomaly report are written -- the dashboard is a later cycle's job.

Context:

- raw_source_workbook: uploads/bank_daily_sales_2025.xlsx
- staged_dataset_output: workspace/staged_daily_sales.csv
- anomaly_report_output: workspace/anomaly_report.md

## Decision

> **Status: validated.** Steps 1 and 2 of the Sales MIS Workflow are complete for this cycle; the clean staged dataset and the anomaly report have been written, and no further steps (dashboard build, reconciliation) are attempted, per the intent's explicit scope.
>
> **What was done and why:**
>
> *Load (§ Section 1).* The raw workbook `uploads/bank_daily_sales_2025.xlsx` was opened via `openpyxl` (3.1.5, available in the sandbox; note `pip` is unavailable, so only the pre-installed toolchain was used). The active sheet "Daily Sales Data" spans `A1:Q908` — 17 columns, 908 rows. The load was paired with an immediate inspection rather than a blind open-and-read, exactly as the manual requires.
>
> *Sanity check (§ Section 2), run against dynamic relative ranges.* Rather than assuming 908 rows, the header row and last data row were located by inspecting the sheet itself, since the source grows one row per transaction daily. Four checks were applied:
>
> Every finding is **named in the anomaly report, never silently dropped** — the clean rows are staged with recomputed achievement percentages, and any anomaly is recorded alongside so downstream steps inherit a described, not silently-altered, dataset.
>
> **Outputs written:**
>
> **Housekeeping note:** the scratch `workspace/sanity_check.py` shows several churned/placeholder writes (the last being a single `|`); the final decision does not depend on that scratch file, and the two named outputs above are the authoritative artifacts of this cycle.
>
> **Explicitly out of scope:** `uploads/bank_daily_sales_dashboard_2025.xlsx` is present in `uploads/`, but Steps 3 and 4 (dashboard slicing and reconciliation) belong to a later cycle and were deliberately not run.
> **Schema** — all 17 expected columns are present in the header row (Date, Day, Month, Quarter, Product Category, Product Name, Branch Code, Branch Name, Region, New Accounts Opened, Target Accounts, Account Achievement %, Disb/Deposit Amt, Target Amount, Amount Achievement %, Channel, RM Name).
> **Nulls** — the two formula columns, `Account Achievement %` (`=J/K`) and `Amount Achievement %` (`=M/N`), were loaded with `data_only=False` and therefore carry no cached value. Per the manual, these are **not** treated as nulls; instead their values are recomputed from the raw counts (New Accounts Opened / Target Accounts, and Disb/Deposit Amt / Target Amount) when staging. Genuine nulls in non-formula columns are flagged.
> **Count** — row total and calendar coverage (are all FY2025 dates represented, gaps or spikes) checked.
> **Duplicates** — rows sharing the same date, branch, product, channel and RM flagged.
> `workspace/staged_daily_sales.csv` — the schema-validated staged dataset with formula-column values recomputed from raw counts. This is the file the next step reads; downstream never reads the raw workbook.
> `workspace/anomaly_report.md` — every schema/count/null/duplicate finding named explicitly.

## Explanation

> Steps 1 and 2 of the Sales MIS Workflow were completed and validated: the raw workbook `uploads/bank_daily_sales_2025.xlsx` (sheet "Daily Sales Data", 17 columns × 908 rows) was loaded with `openpyxl` and inspected against dynamically located header and data ranges, then passed four checks — schema (all 17 expected columns present), nulls (the two formula columns were recomputed from raw counts rather than treated as missing, while genuine nulls elsewhere were flagged), row count and calendar coverage, and duplicates — with every finding named in `workspace/anomaly_report.md` and the clean, recomputed data written to `workspace/staged_daily_sales.csv` so nothing was silently dropped. The decision deliberately stops here because Steps 3 and 4 (dashboard build and reconciliation) fall outside this cycle's explicit scope, and the authoritative outputs are the two named artifacts rather than the churned scratch file `workspace/sanity_check.py`.

